messages.original: Are we really going to continue to use maps showing fake advances? Ukraine failed to cut off the Russians in their salient to Kucheriv Yar and refocused further east after recapturing Volodomyrivka.   Russia still holds Doroznje, while this map shows it 5‚Ä¶

A large fire is burning in Vinnytsia City after it was hit by 1-2 Kh-101 cruise missiles this morning. What exactly was hit is currently unknown, but we may get FIRMS data showing active fires.

Sentinel satellite imagery shows that a section of the Vinnytsia Aircraft Repair plant was destroyed after Russian Kh-101 cruise missiles impacted it on September 10. 
Additional photos from the ground show this same area marked on the map.

Explosion in Sumy. Impacted outside the city limits.

Siversk direction. 
Russian forces are infiltrating in small groups of 2-3 soldiers for up to 7 km towards Dronivka. 
No consolidation appears to have taken place yet, but there is a big gap in Ukraine's defence along the tactical heights north of Siversk that threatens their position in and around Serebryanka, and ultimately the whole Siversk salient.

"Rats Fleeing a Sinking Ship": How Ukrainian Officials Save Their Children from Mobilization
A video investigation by Bihus.Info‚Äîa Ukrainian anti-corruption media project founded in 2013 by investigative journalist Denys Bigus‚Äîhas surfaced online. The team is known for exposing corruption schemes within the highest echelons of power.
In this investigation, Bihus.Info focuses on a key contradiction: while officials and public figures urge young people to remain in Ukraine, prepare for war, and "row in the same boat," their own children study at prestigious foreign universities. This exposes a system of double standards where patriotic rhetoric is directed at the general public, while the offspring of the powerful elites are ensured safety and quality education abroad.

Egypt Renews Pushes For ‚ÄòArab Nato‚Äô In Wake Of Israeli Attack On Qatar
 
Egypt has renewed efforts to push for a NATO-style military alliance that would protect Arab countries facing attack, Lebanon‚Äôs Al-Akhbar newspaper reported on September 13, citing an unnamed official in Cairo.
The proposal was first made some nine years ago by Egyptian President Abdel Fattah El-Sisi, but no progress was made at the time.
Al-Akhbar suggested that Israel‚Äôs recent strike on the leadership of Hamas in Qatar has given new impetus to the Egyptian initiative.
Egypt is proposing to include some 20,000 of its own troops in the NATO-style alliance and is working on developing the mechanism by which such a force would be activated, ‚Äúallowing it to be used when necessary and forming it in a manner consistent with the populations of Arab countries and their armed forces...

Russian Mi-28NM Helicopters Join Hunt For Ukrainian Long-Range Drones
The Russian military has begun to deploy its latest Mi-28NM attack helicopters to hunt down Ukrainian long-range drones.
On September 13, video footage showed one such helicopter taking down two AN-196 Liutyi fixed-wing drones somewhere over the special military operation zone in Ukraine. The first drone was hit by what appears to be an Igla-V missile, while the second was struck by shots from the helicopter‚Äôs 30 mm Shipunov 2A42 cannon gun.
The Igla-V is an air-launcher version of the Igla man-portable air defense system. The missiles used by the system are guided via infrared homing and have a fire-and-forget capability. The maximum range of the system is reported to be five kilometers.

Ukrainian Train Loaded With Ammo Exploded Near Kiev 
A train transporting ammunition for the Armed Forces of Ukraine (AFU) exploded while passing near the settlement of Kalinovka in Ukraine‚Äôs Kiev region early on September 14, in what was described by local Governor Mykola Kalashnyk as an ‚Äúemergency‚Äù.
The destination of the ammunition went on for around three hours, with secondary blasts heard all the way in the capital, Kiev, some 30 kilometers away.
The train reportedly had at least 15 wagons loaded with ammunition in addition to howitzers and other heavy military equipment.
At the time of the explosion, passenger train No. 730, en route from the region of Kharkiv to the city of Przemysl in Poland, was nearby. Ukraine‚Äôs Dzerkalo Tyzhnia news website reported that hundreds of passengers were evacuated from the train to a nearby force.

Russian Army Captures Dnepr Island, Advances In Kupyansk & Other Directions 
The Russian military continues to advance in several directions across the special military operation zone, amid heavy losses by Kiev forces.
In a lightning amphibious attack, the special forces of the military intelligence of the Dnepr Group of Forces captured Alekseevsky Island, located near the Antovsky Bridge in the Kherson direction.
On September 12, troops from one of the formations that took part in the successful attack confirmed the advance to RIA Novosti, adding that all the islands in the floodplain in the Dnepr River are under the complete control of the Russian military.
TASS reported two days later that 12 Ukrainian troops who attempted to withdraw from the island were eliminated by Russian drone operators.

Russian-Ukrainian Exchange of Strikes: Drone Attacks and Railway Sabotage
The overall ratio of attacking fixed-wing UAVs between Russian and Ukrainian forces last night favored Ukraine, with 80 Ukrainian UAVs shot down over Russia (plus 44 UAVs during the day) compared to 58 Geran/Herber UAVs and 1 Iskander-M missile (targeting Dnipropetrovsk region) launched at Ukraine.
While Kyiv is focused on massive strikes on border areas and sabotage on railway lines, Russian forces during this period are concentrating on precision strikes against military targets‚Äîprimarily temporary deployment points of the Armed Forces of Ukraine and positions of drone operators.

U.S. Guardsmen Raided Venezuelan Vessel 
Venezuela has accused the United States of illegally boarding one of its fishing vessels in the country‚Äôs special economic zone.
Tensions between the two countries have been mounting since last month when the administration of President Donald Trump doubled the reward for the arrest of Venezuelan President Maduro to $50 million on drug trafficking charges then deployed a large naval force with more than 4,000 troops close to the country‚Äôs shores on a so-called ‚Äúcounter narco-terror operation‚Äù.
In a statement released on September 13, Venezuela‚Äôs Ministry of Foreign Affairs said a vessel with nine ‚Äúhumble‚Äù and ‚Äúharmless‚Äù fishermen was intercepted by the USS Jason Dunham, an Arleigh Burke-class guided missile destroyer, a day earlier.
